I'll tell you more about it this weekend when I've installed the second one I made.
Let's say the birds will have a better internet connection than mine was in 2015.
Or at least, that was the plan.
The nesting box that already has a nesting box inside uses the home Wi-Fi.
There is still work to be done to connect the other one.
Well, I hung the other nesting box during the day. Here is what it looks like in its good place in the garden.
But, small flashback: "What's inside?", I hear being asked.
On top is one of the ESP32 modules with a fisheye objective camera and an infrared LED that I recovered from a Raspberry Pi device.
If this plastic box has a strange shape, it's because of the pivoting side panel of the nesting box. I bought it like that and wasn't able to modify it, so I had to design my installation around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, the entire setup is powered by a solar panel and a 2,600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here is a photo of the panel.
The gray box suspended on the side of the nesting box houses the battery.
At full charge, it provides me with approximately 4 hours of energy.
I call it a feature. Like this the birds can also have a bit of intimacy.
Initially, I didn't know if the Internet connection in our garden would be good enough for this installation. The old access points I replaced last fall wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover the area well.
It's almost disappointing because I had planned to mount a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and orient it downwards towards the garden.
I could still do it when I install more camera nesting boxes, especially in areas far from the house, I might need it.
Now, for reasons that elude me for the time being, the camera is offline. It turned off just an hour after sunset.
The battery charge may have stopped three hours before sunset due to a lack of light.
Perhaps it wasn't able to charge completely in a bit less than a half-day.
I'll see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have a telemetry system for the battery. I might add one in a future revision.
A few more sensors would be nice, I think.
And maybe a battery that can last the entire night, at least on paper.
Oh, and another lens.
The fisheye is too much.
But I'm already checking out components on Digikey, so I'll maybe just make a custom PCB for this usage after all.
Or not. We'll see.
And, it's still offline.
Super.
